2. Statement of Institutional Concern

The Committee has observed a growing public confusion between execution and judgement.

This confusion has intensified with the arrival of culinary robotics, artificial intelligence recipe systems, factory-prepared convenience meals, and algorithmically optimised food-service environments. These systems perform increasingly impressive tasks. They can calculate macros, reduce waste, standardise preparation, suggest substitutions, optimise stock, and heat substances with unwavering procedural confidence.

However, procedural confidence is not care.

The distinction is not technical but ontological. A burger-flipping robot does not wonder whether the person eating has had a terrible day. A sauce-dispensing mechanism does not detect that the tomatoes are sharper than expected. A menu-generation model does not know that your mother dislikes coriander but pretends not to for reasons dating back to 1998.

These are not inefficiencies. They are the meal.

The Ministry therefore identifies the following risk: that society may come to value only measurable outputs, while neglecting the unmeasurable human decisions through which meals become meaningful.

