5. Theoretical Framework

5.1 The Output Fallacy

The Output Fallacy holds that two things are equivalent if they appear similar at the point of consumption.

Under this doctrine, a machine-made lasagne and a grandmother’s lasagne may be considered comparable if both meet baseline criteria for structure, temperature, sauce distribution, and cheese compliance.

The Ministry rejects this view.

A meal is not exhausted by its visible characteristics. It includes the path by which it arrived, the judgements embedded within it, and the relational field into which it is served.

To ignore this is to confuse the receipt with the gift.

5.2 The Sauce Correction Principle

The Sauce Correction Principle states that no recipe survives first contact with the tomato.

Tomatoes vary in acidity, sweetness, water content, ripeness, season, storage conditions, and moral disposition. A cook responds accordingly. The machine, absent additional sensory and cultural apparatus, executes a protocol derived from idealised tomato behaviour.

The sauce therefore becomes a test site for civilisation.

5.3 The Slightly Burnt Edge Exception

The Slightly Burnt Edge Exception recognises that certain households, families, individuals, regions, and emotionally specific childhoods prefer technically imperfect outcomes.

A machine may identify charring as deviation. A cook may identify it as love.

This distinction cannot be resolved through quality control alone, because the “defect” may be the entire point.

