6. Methodology

The Ministry undertook a multi-stage interpretive evaluation of culinary automation using the following instruments.

6.1 Pan-Dryness Observation Protocol

Researchers observed whether automated systems could determine when a pan was “too dry” before formal smoke generation.

Result: machines detected measurable heat variance, but failed to experience mild internal panic.

6.2 Onion Browning Acceleration Audit

A comparative analysis was conducted between human cooks and automated timing systems.

Human cooks intervened when the onions were “going too fast.” Automated systems waited until the programmed interval expired, thereby producing onions that were legally brown but spiritually accused.

6.3 Maternal Preference Sensitivity Index

Systems were assessed for their ability to account for a mother’s stated and unstated food preferences.

AI systems successfully retrieved general dietary preferences, historical recipes, and plausible comfort-food recommendations.

They failed to detect the crucial distinction between:

* “She says she does not mind,” and
* “She absolutely minds.”

6.4 Quiet Child Detection Trial

Subjects were seated at a dinner table. One child became quiet.

Human cooks adjusted tone, portion size, conversational approach, and dessert policy.

Machine systems registered silence as reduced acoustic interference and continued service.

6.5 Recursive Recipe Collapse Exercise

An automated recipe generator was instructed to produce a meal expressing care. When asked how it knew care had been expressed, it generated additional procedural steps. When asked how those steps became care, it generated a garnish.

The garnish was adequate but evasive.

