7. Findings

7.1 Recipes Are Maps, Not Journeys

The recipe is useful, but it is not sovereign. It cannot smell the fish, feel the dough, remember the oven runs hot, or know that today is not a day for impressive food.

The cook reads the recipe, then disobeys it responsibly.

7.2 Standardisation Produces Reliability, Not Meaning

Standardisation is valuable where safety, efficiency, and predictability are required. However, excessive standardisation removes the very deviations through which human attention becomes legible.

A meal prepared for someone is often meaningful because it has been adjusted for them.

7.3 Care Is Not an Ingredient

Care cannot be added at step seven, folded gently, and baked until golden.

Care is distributed across the entire process. It appears in the decision to lower the flame now, not in ninety seconds. It appears in the judgement that the sauce needs acid. It appears in serving a person something familiar when novelty would be cruel.

7.4 The Machine Does Not Know Who Is Hungry

A machine can produce food for a consumer category. A cook can cook for this person, in this room, on this day, after what just happened.

This is not a minor distinction. It is the governing distinction.

