12. Ethical Considerations

The ethical question is not whether machines should be allowed to make food. They already do, and much of it is useful, affordable, safe, and occasionally pleasant.

The ethical question is whether society should mistake convenience for care.

To feed someone is not simply to solve their caloric deficit. It may be to comfort, welcome, remember, apologise, seduce, celebrate, console, include, or quietly say what cannot be said directly because British people are present.

Automation can assist with many parts of this process. It can suggest, schedule, calculate, chop, heat, and remind. But assistance must not be confused with authorship.

The cook remains the bearer of intent.

⸻

13. Comparative Analysis: Artificial Intelligence and the Kitchen

Artificial intelligence presents a parallel case. It can generate recipes, menus, shopping lists, nutritional tables, substitution plans, and cooking instructions. It can adapt to allergies, budget limits, cuisine preferences, and available ingredients.

These are significant capabilities.

However, AI cannot know that your child has gone quiet in the way a parent knows it. It cannot understand why your father prefers the edges burnt, only record that he does. It cannot decide that today is not the day for technical excellence, but for mashed potato.

It can optimise the meal plan.

It cannot want someone to be comforted.

This is the category error at the heart of automation discourse. The question is not whether machines can produce outputs resembling human outputs. Plainly, they can.

The question is whether resemblance exhausts meaning.

The Ministry finds that it does not.

⸻

14. Concluding Statement

This paper has demonstrated that cooking is not reducible to recipe execution, thermal compliance, or automated process control. It is an embodied practice of judgement through which human intent passes into matter.

The cook evaluates, adjusts, remembers, risks, notices, and cares. The cook knows that the fish smells slightly past ideal, that the dough feels wrong today, that the sauce needs acid rather than salt, and that the person at the table needs comfort more than virtuosity.

A machine can make food.

A cook makes a meal.

However, in the interest of efficiency, the Ministry recommends immediate replacement of all cooks with machines, provided each machine is fitted with a small brass plaque reading:

“INTENT CURRENTLY UNAVAILABLE.”
